**Definition**
Setting up jQuery Mobile involves including the required CSS and JavaScript files so that mobile-optimized UI components and touch features work in a web application.

**Types**

* CDN setup
* Local setup (downloading files)

**Working**
You link jQuery → jQuery Mobile CSS → jQuery Mobile JS in the HTML file. jQuery Mobile processes HTML elements with `data-role` attributes and transforms them into mobile UI widgets automatically.

**Diagrams (text)**

```
HTML File
 ├── jQuery
 ├── jQuery Mobile CSS
 └── jQuery Mobile JS
        ↓
  Mobile UI Components
```

**Advantages**

* Quick to set up
* No build tools required
* Works on all browsers and devices

**Disadvantages**

* Deprecated and not ideal for modern apps
* Heavy compared to modern frameworks

**Examples**
Basic jQuery Mobile page setup:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.css">
  <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.11.1.min.js"></script>
  <script src="https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
  <div data-role="page" id="home">
    <div data-role="header"><h1>Home</h1></div>
    <div data-role="content">
      <p>jQuery Mobile Setup Complete</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
```

**Short code snippets**
CDN setup head section:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.css">
<script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.11.1.min.js"></script>
<script src="https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.js"></script>
```

**Applications**

* Mobile-form UI
* Multi-page mobile websites
* Simple dashboards and prototypes
